<DOC><DOCNO> AP890811-0211 </DOCNO><FILEID>AP-NR-08-11-89 1154EDT</FILEID><FIRST>r d BC-SearsCuts     08-11 0214</FIRST><SECOND>BC-Sears Cuts,0221</SECOND><HEAD>Sears Cuts 104 Jobs at Telemarketing Headquarters</HEAD><DATELINE>CHICAGO (AP) </DATELINE><TEXT>   Sears, Roebuck and Co. said it will reduce bynearly half the 250-member workforce at its telemarketing operationas part of continuing cutbacks in its merchandise group staff.   Sears, which this week cut jobs in its catalog headquarters,said Wednesday that 104 of the employees at its suburban Chicagofacility, most of them part time, will be terminated at thecompany's credit telemarketing and shop-at-home direct-marketingservices departments by Oct. 6.   Many of those remaining in the two departments will be part-timeworkers, as opposed to full time.   ``The reason for this reorganization is that their business iscyclical,'' said a Sears spokeswoman. ``We want better coverage onthe phones, and part-time employees are more suited to that.''   The credit telemarketing operation, which handles 800-numbercredit inquiries and credit solicitation, will move to existingfacilities in Knoxville, Tenn., in October. About 80 jobs in thatdepartment, including those of 20 full-time workers, will beeliminated.   In the direct-response department, 24 full-time workers will becut, leaving 136 part-time workers behind to handle the job.   The cuts are all part of Sears' previously announcedwide-ranging restructuring program, which includes reducing itsSears Merchandise Group staff. Sears is the nation's largestretailer.</TEXT></DOC>